2026-02-27 05:59:30 | IngestionPipeline | INFO | Extraction Completed: summary='James P. Comer is a leading child psychiatrist known for his work improving scholastic performance in disadvantaged children and founding the Comer School Development Program. He has authored numerous books and articles on child psychiatry, race relations, and education.' domain='Professional' entities=[Entity(name='James P. Comer', type='Person', importance=0.5, isolated_context='James P. Comer (born James Pierpont Comer, September 25, 1934 in East Chicago, Indiana) is currently the Maurice Falk Professor of Child Psychiatry at the Yale Child Study Center and has been since 1976. He is also an associate dean at the Yale School of Medicine. As one of the world\'s leading child psychiatrists, he is best known for his efforts to improve the scholastic performance of children from lower-income and minority backgrounds which led to the founding of the Comer School Development Program in 1968. His program has been used in more than 600 schools in eighty-two school districts. He is the author of ten books, including the autobiographical "Maggie\'s American Dream: The Life and Times of a Black Family", 1988; "Leave No Child Behind: Preparing Today\'s Youth for Tomorrow\'s World", 2004; and his most recent book, "What I Learned in School: Reflections on Race, Child Development, and School Reform", 2009. He has also written more than 150 articles for Parents (magazine) and more than 300 articles on children\'s health and development and race relations. Dr. Comer has also served as a consultant to the Children\'s Television Workshop (Sesame Workshop) which produces Sesame Street and The Electric Company (1971 TV series). He is a co-founder and past president of the Black Psychiatrists of America and has served on the board of several universities, foundations, and corporations. He has also lectured and consulted widely not only across the United States at different universities, medical schools, and scientific associations, but also around the world in places such as London, Paris, Tokyo, Dakar, Senegal and Sydney, Australia. For his work and scholarship, Dr. Comer has been awarded 47 honorary degrees and has been recognized by numerous organizations.')] concepts=[Concept(name='Child Psychiatry', definition='', isolated_context="As one of the world's leading child psychiatrists, he is best known for his efforts to improve the scholastic performance of children from lower-income and minority backgrounds which led to the founding of the Comer School Development Program in 1968."), Concept(name='Education Reform', definition='', isolated_context='He is best known for his efforts to improve the scholastic performance of children from lower-income and minority backgrounds which led to the founding of the Comer School Development Program in 1968.')] tasks=[] persona_traits=[] references=[ExternalReference(title="Maggie's American Dream: The Life and Times of a Black Family", type='Book', content="Maggie's American Dream: The Life and Times of a Black Family", source='James P. Comer', isolated_context=''), ExternalReference(title="Leave No Child Behind: Preparing Today's Youth for Tomorrow's World", type='Book', content="Leave No Child Behind: Preparing Today's Youth for Tomorrow's World", source='James P. Comer', isolated_context=''), ExternalReference(title='What I Learned in School: Reflections on Race, Child Development, and School Reform', type='Book', content='What I Learned in School: Reflections on Race, Child Development, and School Reform', source='James P. Comer', isolated_context='')] relationships=[] sentiment='Neutral'
